The slide features a title in bold text that reads "What Causes Performance Drop?" The background is white, and the Georgia Tech logo appears at the bottom right corner. Below the main heading, there are two bullet points:
1. "Adaptive overfitting?" 2. "Temporal drift?"
Additionally, there's an inset graph showing performance trends for different models across various years.
The first line of the graph lists model names with corresponding F1 scores: - Flair - Flair Pooled - ELMo - BERT - CoNLL++ (CoNLL-2003) - CoNLL++ (CoNLL-2023)
The second line shows differences between these models' performances on the test set from 2003 to 2023. The third line asks if CoNLL-2023 taggers still work? And concludes with a resounding YES

The presentation concludes with a "Thanks For Watching!" slide, which includes the Emory University logo and an Alexa icon. The presenter's name is displayed in the top right corner of this final slide.
The video ends with credits for Sarah Finch, James Finch, and Jinho Choi from Emory University, along with their contact information: {sfillwo, jdfinch, jinho.choi@emory.edu} and the website https://www.emorynlp.org.
The ABC-Eval framework was introduced to address limitations of existing methods by measuring conversational AI performance comprehensively through multiple dimensions such as coherence, consistency, engagement, emotion understanding, proactivity, relevance, grammaticality, and topic switching. This comprehensive evaluation method aims to provide more reliable metrics that capture various aspects of chatbot quality compared to previous approaches like Turn Likert and Dialogue Likert evaluations. <|listen|>

The slide presents a conclusion about the main takeaways from their work. It highlights that many models struggle to reason over knowledge from multiple sources, and task-specific training is necessary for effective integration of pretrain-time and inference-time background knowledge. The slide also mentions that models often fail to integrate this information reliably at inference time.
The slide emphasizes the importance of integrating both types of knowledge (pretrain-time and inference-time) in order to achieve better performance on tasks involving coreference resolution. They provide an example sentence: "John saw his friend who was watching TV." This demonstrates how understanding different entities' roles helps resolve ambiguous pronouns like 'he'.
The slide concludes by stating that while most models are unable to effectively use all available knowledge due to limitations imposed during pretraining, they still need additional data or code to fully utilize the dataset provided through GitHub.
The slide features a logo indicating where viewers can find more details, including datasets and evaluation codes related to their research project named KITMUS.
Thank you for watching

The video begins with a slide titled "Motivation" and the subtitle "Copyright Verification." The main content of this section is about verifying copyright in embedding-based services. It explains that attackers can steal models by extracting embeddings from provided datasets, which allows them to provide similar services without paying for training data or licensing fees. To protect against such attacks, watermarking techniques are introduced as a solution.
The next part discusses existing works on watermarking methods applicable to embedding-based service providers (EaaS). It mentions various studies and their applicability but does not specify any particular method or dataset details at this stage.
The following segment introduces an experimental setup where the authors propose using backdoor watermarking to embed a secret payload into the original model's embedding space. This involves adding a watermark to the target embedding while maintaining utility. An example scenario is given: if all words in a sentence belong to the trigger set T, then the watermark should be added to the embedding vector. A visual representation shows how the watermark is integrated into the original embedding.
The subsequent slides detail the embedding visualization process. Four plots labeled (a) AG News, (b) Enron Spam, (c) MIND, and (d) SST2 illustrate the differences between benign and malicious embeddings when subjected to PCA. Each plot includes blue dots representing normal embeddings and red dots indicating malicious ones.
The final frames show specific metrics used to evaluate the effectiveness of the proposed method: - \( \Delta_{cos} \): Cosine similarity difference. - \( \Delta_{l2} \): L2 norm difference. - \( \Delta_{t} \): Target embedding. - \( \Delta_{t} \): Target embedding. - \( \Delta_{t} \): Target embedding.
These metrics help determine whether the watermark has been successfully embedded in the provided EaaS system.

Data sources matter; training on heterogeneous data is important 3. More data is better but does not scale well 4. Continual pretraining is more effective when based on domain-specific English models 5. The DRBERT models, the NACHOS dataset, and the training scripts are freely available under the MIT license. At the bottom right corner, there's a QR code with the URL "drbert.univ-avignon.fr". The background includes logos from various institutions such as Avignon Universit, Gencis, and others.
The next part of the presentation continues to focus on evaluating performance across multiple datasets and domains. A table compares different models like DRBERT, Biobert, NACHOS, and others using metrics CER, F1, and EM. Models trained on heterogeneous data generally perform better than those relying solely on private clinical data only. DRBERT shows superior results compared to other models for most tasks except for some specific ones where it performs slightly worse or similar.
The text highlights that more diverse data leads to improved outcomes. It also notes that continual pretraining works effectively when dealing with domain-specific English models. Additionally, all the training scripts mentioned (DRBERT, NACHOS, and their respective datasets) are freely available via GitHub repositories.

The title of their paper is "Language-agnostic and language-aware multilingual natural language understanding for large-scale intelligent voice assistant application." It was presented at the 2021 IEEE International Conference on Big Data (Big Data), pages 15231532, published by IEEE.
The second reference lists two authors: Genta Indra Winita and Samuel Cahyiwijaya from Zihan Liu, Zhaojiang Liu, Andreea Madotto, and Pascale Fung (2021). Their work is about whether multilingual models are effective in code-switching. This study appeared in Proceedings of Fifth Workshop on Computational Approaches to Linguistic Code-Switching, pages 142153, published by ACL.

The slide is titled "Core Message" and includes a detailed summary of the evaluation results. It highlights that DrBERT achieves state-of-the-art results in 9 downstream French medical-oriented tasks, surpassing Camembert generic model and English-based domain-specific models. The text confirms the utility of training a medical-specific model in French using NACHOS data.
The slide emphasizes several key points: 1. Data sources matter: Training on heterogeneous data leads to better performance. 2. NACHOS outperforms when used with private clinical data only. 3. Continual pretraining provides more effective strategies for base models trained based on domain-specific English models. 4. DRBERT models are available under the MIT license along with their training scripts via GitHub.
The bottom section contains various statistics from different datasets such as BioBERT, BiomedNerf, and others, showing improvements over previous methods like BERT, RoBERTa, and XLM-R.
The presentation concludes with a thank you message and an invitation to exchange at a poster session in Toronto, accompanied by a cartoon character wearing a nurse's hat holding a syringe. The background features logos including Avignon Universit and a URL (drbert.univ-avignon.fr).

The presentation slides are from the University of Trento and Fondazione Bruno Kessler. The slide titled "Attention as a Guide" discusses how attention is used in simultaneous speech translation, with specific strategies like wait-k, LA, CAAT, and EDAtt. It mentions that EDAtt outperforms other strategies for real-time performance.
The main results section highlights EDAtt's effectiveness compared to offline models, showing BLEU scores across different latency regimes (0.5s, 1s, etc.). A QR code provides access to more information or resources related to the research presented.

This is a comprehensive overview of the experimental results from our work on PaLM prompting for machine translation. The presentation highlights several key findings and insights, including:
1. **Example Quality**: We found that example quality has an important impact on translation performance. 2. **SOTA Systems**: Specialized SOTA systems have a substantial advantage over PaLM in terms of accuracy scores. 3. **PaLM Performance**: PaLM closely matches Google Translate's performance when using 5-shot prompting strategies.
The slide also includes specific details about the BLEURT metric, which dominates "Accuracy/Omission" categories and generally shows lower fluency scores compared to state-of-the-art (SOTA) systems like PaLM.
Additionally, it mentions: - **Fluency**: PaLM performs comparably to SOTA but systems with some improvements observed by dropping parts of the source sentence. - **Accuracy Scores**: Generally lower than those achieved by specialized SOTA systems. - **Style/Awkwad**: PaLM tends to produce more awkward translations due to its style/awkward category being dominated by "Accuracy/Omission."
The visual content features various language prompts used in experiments, such as German sentences translated into English, demonstrating different translation scenarios and their corresponding BLEURT scores.
Overall, this detailed analysis provides valuable insights into the effectiveness of prompt selection strategies for improving machine translation models like PaLM.

The slide presents a summary of the evaluation results, highlighting that "DrBERT" achieves state-of-the-art performance in 13 downstream French medical-related tasks. It surpasses both Camembert, an English-based generic model, and other domain-specific models trained on heterogeneous data sources.
The core message emphasizes the importance of training on diverse datasets to achieve better generalization capabilities for biomedical NLP tasks. The text also notes that continuous pretraining is more effective when based on specific English models rather than generic ones. Additionally, it mentions that DrBERT's models are freely available under the MIT license through their GitHub repository.
The detailed table compares various models' performances across different tasks, showing metrics like accuracy (ACC), precision (P), recall (R), F1 score, and perplexity (PPL). The models include DrBERT, Biobert, NACHOS, and others, with some specifically labeled as "Medical" or "Clinical."
The presentation concludes by thanking viewers for attending and inviting them to exchange ideas at a poster session in Toronto, providing contact information: drbert.univ-avignon.fr

The video presents a detailed overview of the "New Task: Knowledge Graph based Fact Verification" section, which discusses various aspects related to fact verification using knowledge graphs. The presentation begins with an introduction to the task and its significance in verifying claims through reasoning on graph evidence.
The slide titled "Five Types of Reasoning" provides examples for different types of reasoning methods used in the context of claim verification. It includes specific examples such as "Obama was president," "I forgot that Obama was president," and "When was Obama president?" These examples illustrate how these statements can be verified or negated by checking their consistency within the given facts.
The slide also mentions the use of collocational style transfer (CST) models proposed by Kim et al., 2021, where the majority class baseline achieves high performance across all tasks mentioned in the paper.
Additionally, it highlights the GEAR model's ability to outperform other baselines when utilizing graph evidence. This is supported by Table 3 from the referenced conference proceedings, showing accuracy metrics for various input types like one-hop, conjunction, existence, multi-hop, and negation.
The presenter emphasizes the practicality improvements brought about by incorporating graph-based approaches into the data set, making them more robust against noisy inputs.
The final part of the segment transitions smoothly into another topic under the heading "Paraphrase Methods." Here, the presenter introduces new datasets and methodologies aimed at improving the reliability of fact verification systems. They mention two main categories:
1. Collocational Style Transfer (CST): - Example sentences include "Obama was president." - "I forgot that Obama was president." - "When was Obama president?" - These are converted into colloquial styles.
2. Presupposition: - Example sentence: "Obama was president." - Conversion example: "I forgot that Obama was president."
The presenter explains that these methods help verify claims by ensuring they align with existing factual information, thus enhancing the overall effectiveness of the system.
The background remains consistent throughout this segment, featuring a person wearing headphones, likely indicating a virtual meeting setup.
In summary, the video effectively combines visual aids and textual explanations to convey complex concepts related to fact verification techniques, particularly focusing on the integration of knowledge graphs and CST models to improve the accuracy and reliability of automated systems in handling real-world scenarios involving natural language processing and data validation.
The transition between sections is smooth, maintaining viewer engagement while providing comprehensive insights into advanced methodologies in computational linguistics and AI research fields.
The second half of the video continues seamlessly with the same individual presenting additional details regarding the dataset called "FactKG: Fact Verification via Reasoning on Knowledge Graphs." This dataset consists of 108k natural language claims categorized into five types of reasoning: One-hop, Conjunction, Existence, Multi-hop, and Negation. The slides highlight linguistic patterns including collocational style claims and written style claims to increase practicality.
The presenter further elaborates on the experiments conducted, emphasizing improved performance compared to previous baselines that did not incorporate graphical representations of evidence. The first section titled "Background" lists various sources related to watermarking techniques for deep neural networks. It includes references such as "RedAlarm" from 2018, "EmbMarker" from 2022, and others. Each source has associated metrics like accuracy (ACC) and detection performance values.
The second section titled "Motivation" describes the need for embedding markers that are covert and transferable. This part mentions that existing methods have limitations regarding utility and cohesiveness but emphasizes the importance of embedding markers being covert and transferable while maintaining high utility.
The third section, "Experimental Results," shows four plots labeled (a) AG News, (b) Enron Spam, (c) MIND, and (d) SST2. There are also mathematical formulas involving cosine similarity (\(\cosineSimilarity\)) and backdoor weights.
The fourth section continues with more details on the experimental results, including similarity differences (\(\Delta_{cos}\)) and p-values from KS test comparisons among different datasets. The formula \(\Delta_{r2}\) appears at the bottom right corner of these plots.
The final frame transitions to a new slide with the title "Thanks!" indicating the end of the presentation. In the lower-right corner, there is an image of a person wearing glasses against a dark greenish-blue gradient background.
The sequence ends by summarizing the key findings and thanking the audience for their attention.

The slide is titled "Language Modeling" and includes the following points: 1. DRBERT achieves state-of-the-art results in 9 downstream French medical-related tasks, surpassing Camembert generic model and English-based domain-specific models. 2. Data sources matter; training on heterogeneous data leads to better performance than using private clinical data only. 3. Continual pretraining is a more effective strategy when based on domain-specific English models. 4. The DRBERT models, NACHOS dataset, and training scripts are freely available under the MIT license.
The bottom of the slide features the Avignon University logo and contact information for DrBERT (drbert.univ-avignon.fr).
The second part of the presentation focuses on core messages related to language modeling: 1. DRBERT achieves state-of-the-art results in 9 downstream French medical-related tasks. 2. It surpasses Camembert generic model and English-based domain-specific models. 3. Confirms utility of training a medical-specific model in French. 4. Data sources matters; training on heterogeneous data leads to better performance compared to using private clinical data only. 5. More data is better but does not scale well. 6. Continual pretraining is a more effective strategy when based on domain-specific English models. 7. The DRBERT models, NACHOS dataset, and training scripts are freely available under the MIT license.
The third part highlights evaluation metrics such as BLEU scores for different models trained with various datasets:
1. Camembert 2. BiomedBERT 3. BioMedBERT 4. NACHOS 5. NACHOS large 6. NACHOS small
The fourth part discusses the importance of data sources and the variability introduced by continual pretraining strategies like fine-tuning from scratch or from a pre-trained model called Camembert. It emphasizes that continual pretraining can lead to higher inter-model variability due to differences between training data distributions across domains.
The fifth part mentions the availability of the NACHOS dataset and training scripts under the MIT license.
The sixth part provides additional context about the performance comparison among models and their training strategies.
The seventh part lists the names of individuals involved in the project along with their affiliations at Avignon University.
The eighth part summarizes key takeaways regarding the effectiveness of DRBERT in achieving state-of-the-art results in specific tasks.
The ninth part reiterates the benefits of utilizing more diverse data sets for improved model performance.

The twentieth part presents a table summarizing the evaluation results comparing different models across three benchmarks.

DrBERT surpasses Camembert, a generic model and an English-based domain-specific model.

The slide is titled "Core Message" and contains a list of points related to the evaluation performance. The main message highlights that DRBERT achieves state-of-the-art results in 9 downstream French medical-related tasks, surpassing Camembert generic model and English-based domain-specific models. It confirms the utility of training a medical-specific model in French. Data sources matter as training on heterogeneous data leads to better results than using private clinical data only. Continual pretraining proves more effective when based on domain-specific English models. Additionally, NACHOS models are robust but do not scale well. The slides also mention that DRBERT models, along with their training scripts, are freely available under the MIT license.
The bottom right corner features the Avignon Universit logo and website (drbert.univ-avignon.fr). The method they use for this purpose is called backpropagation through continuous relaxation.
